@page "/learn/poet"
@layout Consensus.Web.Components.Layout.MainLayout

<PageTitle>Proof of Elapsed Time · Tutorials · Consensus Lab</PageTitle>

<TutorialPage Title="Proof of Elapsed Time (PoET)"
              Lede="Each computer rolls a fair wait timer inside a tamper-proof chip. Whoever waits the shortest wins the round — no electricity bonfire required."
              Difficulty="Advanced"
              ReadTime="~10 min">

    <h2>The basic idea</h2>

    <p>
        Proof of Work wastes energy because every miner has to actually <em>compute</em>
        billions of hashes to prove they "tried hard". What if you could skip the computing
        but keep the lottery? That's what Intel asked when they invented Proof of Elapsed Time
        in 2016.
    </p>

    <p>
        PoET runs inside a special hardware feature called a <strong>Trusted Execution
        Environment</strong> (TEE) — a tamper-proof region of an Intel CPU. Each round, every
        participant asks their TEE to generate a random wait time. They sleep that long. When
        their timer expires, they get a signed certificate from the TEE saying "Yes, this
        machine really did wait that long". The shortest waiter wins the round.
    </p>

    <div class="analogy">
        <strong>Analogy:</strong> Imagine a board game where everyone draws a random number
        from 1 to 60 from a sealed envelope. Whoever drew the smallest number goes first this
        turn. The envelope is sealed so nobody can peek; the rules say everyone has to wait
        their number of seconds before claiming victory; everyone watching can verify the
        signature on the envelope. No racing, no shouting — just fair waiting.
    </div>

    <h2>How a round works, step by step</h2>

    <MermaidDiagram Caption="A PoET round: each node's TEE issues a random wait time, shortest waiter wins.">
flowchart TD
    Start([Round starts]) --> Request[Every node asks its TEE<br/>for a random wait time]
    Request --> Wait[Each node sleeps<br/>until its timer expires]
    Wait --> Race{Whose timer<br/>expires first?}
    Race --> Winner[Winner asks TEE<br/>for a signed certificate]
    Winner --> Broadcast[Winner broadcasts<br/>block + TEE attestation]
    Broadcast --> Verify[Others verify the<br/>TEE signature is valid]
    Verify --> Accept{Signature OK?}
    Accept -- Yes --> Commit[Block is added<br/>to the chain]
    Accept -- No --> Reject[Block rejected,<br/>round restarts]
    Commit --> Start
    Reject --> Start
    </MermaidDiagram>

    <h2>Watch a round play out</h2>

    <p>
        Six validators each ask their TEE chip for a random wait time. The numbers under
        each node show how long they have to sleep this round. Whoever drew the shortest
        wait wakes up first, gets a signed certificate from their TEE, and broadcasts the
        block to everyone else.
    </p>

    <ConsensusAnimation Title="Proof of Elapsed Time — shortest waiter wins"
                        Actors="@_poetActors" Steps="@_poetSteps" />

@code {
    private static readonly List<ConsensusAnimation.Actor> _poetActors = BuildPoetActors();

    private static List<ConsensusAnimation.Actor> BuildPoetActors()
    {
        var ring = AnimationLayouts.RingWithCentre(
            peripheralCount: 6,
            centreId: "tee",
            centreLabel: "Intel SGX",
            centreColor: "#8e44ad",
            centreIcon: "🔒",
            peripheralIdPrefix: "n",
            peripheralLabelPrefix: "Node",
            peripheralIcon: "⏱");
        // Each node's "wait time" appears under its label.
        var waits = new[] { "wait 18s", "wait 7s", "wait 24s", "wait 11s", "wait 31s", "wait 14s" };
        for (int i = 1; i < ring.Count; i++)
        {
            ring[i] = ring[i] with { SubLabel = waits[i - 1] };
        }
        return ring;
    }

    private static readonly List<ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep> _poetSteps = new()
    {
        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "1. Each node asks its TEE for a wait time",
            Description: "Every node calls into its hardware-protected Trusted Execution Environment (Intel SGX). The TEE rolls a fair random wait time and returns it sealed.",
            Messages: AnimationLayouts.Broadcast("tee", new[] {"n1","n2","n3","n4","n5","n6"},
                color: "#9b59b6", label: "wait").ToList(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"tee"}),

        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "2. Every node sleeps its assigned time",
            Description: "Each node waits exactly the number of seconds its TEE prescribed. Node 2 drew 7s — the shortest — so they wake up first.",
            Messages: new List<ConsensusAnimation.Message>(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"n1","n2","n3","n4","n5","n6"}),

        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "3. Node 2's timer expires — they win!",
            Description: "Node 2 wakes up, asks the TEE for a signed certificate proving they really did wait that long, and builds a block.",
            Messages: new List<ConsensusAnimation.Message>
            {
                new("n2", "tee", "#9b59b6", "ack", DelayMs: 0, DurationMs: 700),
                new("tee", "n2", "#9b59b6", "cert", DelayMs: 700, DurationMs: 700),
            },
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"n2","tee"}),

        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "4. Winner broadcasts block + TEE attestation",
            Description: "Node 2 sends the block plus the TEE-signed certificate to every other node. Anyone can verify the attestation against Intel's hardware key.",
            Messages: AnimationLayouts.Broadcast("n2", new[] {"n1","n3","n4","n5","n6"},
                color: "#388e3c", label: "block+cert").ToList(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"n2"}),

        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "5. Others verify and accept",
            Description: "Each peer checks the TEE signature in milliseconds. The block is added; everyone asks their TEE for a fresh wait time and the cycle starts again.",
            Messages: new List<ConsensusAnimation.Message>(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"n1","n2","n3","n4","n5","n6","tee"}),
    };
}

    <h2>The Trusted Execution Environment</h2>

    <p>
        The whole protocol hinges on a TEE — a feature on certain Intel CPUs called
        <strong>SGX</strong> (Software Guard Extensions). Think of SGX as a tiny vault inside
        your CPU. Code running inside the vault is cryptographically isolated from the rest
        of the operating system — even from a privileged attacker who owns the machine.
        Programs outside the vault can <em>ask</em> the vault to do things and get back signed
        answers, but they can't see inside or modify what's there.
    </p>

    <p>
        For PoET, the TEE does two jobs:
    </p>

    <ol>
        <li>
            <strong>Generates a fair random wait time</strong> from a verified random source.
            Because the code runs inside the vault, the participant can't peek at their own
            number ahead of time or bias the lottery.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Issues a signed certificate</strong> when the timer truly expires — not a
            millisecond earlier. The certificate uses the TEE's hardware-attested key, which
            other nodes can verify.
        </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Why this is clever</h2>

    <p>
        PoET gives you most of the security properties of PoW — random fair leader selection,
        verifiable proof that the winner "did the work" — without the electricity cost. The
        "work" in PoET is just waiting, which is essentially free. Yet you still can't cheat
        the lottery, because the TEE controls the timer and the OS can't tamper with it.
    </p>

    <p>
        It's also fast: rounds typically take 1–5 seconds compared to Bitcoin's 10 minutes.
        And every node's chance of winning is uniform regardless of CPU power — a Raspberry Pi
        with SGX (in theory) has the same odds as a giant data centre.
    </p>

    <h2>The catch — TEE trust</h2>

    <p>
        PoET's biggest weakness is its dependency on Intel. By using SGX, the entire network
        is implicitly trusting that:
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>Intel's SGX implementation is secure (it has had several vulnerabilities — see Foreshadow, Plundervolt, ÆPIC Leak).</li>
        <li>Intel hasn't backdoored the platform.</li>
        <li>Intel's attestation servers (used to verify SGX certificates) stay online and uncompromised.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        This is the opposite philosophy from PoW, where the only trust is in cryptographic
        math. PoET trades cryptographic purity for energy efficiency — and it's only as
        secure as the underlying hardware platform.
    </p>

    <h2>The real-world picture</h2>

    <p>
        PoET was designed for <strong>Hyperledger Sawtooth</strong>, an enterprise blockchain
        framework. Sawtooth was used by Walmart and a handful of others for supply-chain
        tracking, but adoption has been muted — partly because the SGX requirement limits
        which hardware can participate, and partly because Hyperledger Fabric (which uses
        PBFT) has been more popular for the same use cases.
    </p>

    <h2>Strengths and trade-offs</h2>

    <div class="pro-con-grid">
        <div class="pro-card">
            <h4>✅ Strengths</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Energy-efficient — waiting is free</li>
                <li>Faster block times than PoW</li>
                <li>Hardware-enforced fair lottery, no stake required</li>
                <li>Familiar PoW-like security model without the energy cost</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="con-card">
            <h4>⚠️ Trade-offs</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Requires Intel SGX (or compatible TEE) on every validator</li>
                <li>Trusts Intel as a hardware authority</li>
                <li>Historical SGX vulnerabilities undermine the trust model</li>
                <li>Less battle-tested than PoW, PoS, or PBFT</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>What our simulator does (and doesn't) capture</h2>

    <p>
        The simulator implements PoET's <em>algorithmic</em> behaviour — random wait times,
        shortest waiter wins — but it doesn't have real TEE hardware to attest to anything.
        Instead, we use a seeded software RNG, which makes the protocol reproducible (the
        thesis values determinism) but means we're not really proving the wait. We document
        this limitation in the thesis as a deferred item: integrating a real TEE attestation
        path is future work.
    </p>

    <p>
        For the demo this is fine — what we're studying is fairness across leaders, throughput,
        and round-time variance, all of which the simulator captures faithfully.
    </p>

    <div class="try-it">
        <h3>🎮 Try it in the simulator</h3>
        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-2">
            Run a PoET simulation with 10 nodes and seed=42. The Specialized Analytics → PoET
            tab shows a histogram of wait times — that distribution should look roughly
            exponential (a property of fair Poisson processes), which is the same shape PoW
            block intervals follow.
        </MudText>
        <MudButton Variant="Variant.Filled" Color="Color.Primary"
                   EndIcon="@Icons.Material.Filled.PlayCircle"
                   Href="/simulations">Run a PoET simulation</MudButton>
        <MudButton Variant="Variant.Text" Color="Color.Primary"
                   EndIcon="@Icons.Material.Filled.QueryStats"
                   Href="/specialized-analytics">View PoET analytics</MudButton>
    </div>

